(L.) J. Wen &amp; Boggan].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Nine species with eight occurring in warm temperate to tropical areas of eastern and southeastern Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Suessenguth, K" journalOrPublisher="Repertorium Specierum Novarum Regni Vegetabilis" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" pagination="5 - 15" publicationUrl="10.1002/fedr.19400490104" refId="B14" refString="Suessenguth, K, 1940. Einige neue und seltene Amarantaceen, Rhamnaceen und Vitaceen. Repertorium Specierum Novarum Regni Vegetabilis 49: 5 - 15, DOI: 10.1002/fedr.19400490104" title="Einige neue und seltene Amarantaceen, Rhamnaceen und Vitaceen." url="10.1002/fedr.19400490104" volume="49" year="1940">Suessenguth 1940</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Galet, P" journalOrPublisher="Universite de Montpellier, Montpellier" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" refId="B4" refString="Galet, P, 1967. Recherches sur les Methods d'identification et de Classification des Vitacees Temperees. Universite de Montpellier, Montpellier" title="Recherches sur les Methods d'identification et de Classification des Vitacees Temperees" year="1967">Galet 1967</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, ZD" editor="Wu ,, CY" journalOrPublisher="Flora of China" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" pagination="173 - 222" refId="B3" refString="Chen, ZD, Ren, H, Wen, J, 2007. Vitaceae. Flora of China vol. 12: 173 - 222" title="Vitaceae." volume="vol. 12" volumeTitle="Flora of China" year="2007">Chen et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
), and one species distributed in eastern North America extending to the Caribbean (
<bibRefCitation author="Brizicky, GK" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Arnold Arboretum" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" pagination="48 - 67" refId="B2" refString="Brizicky, GK, 1965. The genera of Vitaceae in the southeastern United States. Journal of the Arnold Arboretum 46: 48 - 67" title="The genera of Vitaceae in the southeastern United States." volume="46" year="1965">Brizicky 1965</bibRefCitation>
). This intercontinental disjunct distribution between eastern Asia and eastern North America represent a classical biogeographic pattern of the Northern Hemisphere (
<bibRefCitation author="Wen, J" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" pagination="421 - 455" publicationUrl="10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.30.1.421" refId="B16" refString="Wen, J, 1999. Evolution of eastern Asian and eastern North American disjunct pattern in flowering plants. Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics 30: 421 - 455, DOI: 10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.30.1.421" title="Evolution of eastern Asian and eastern North American disjunct pattern in flowering plants." url="10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.30.1.421" volume="30" year="1999">Wen 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wen, J" editor="Long, M" journalOrPublisher="Higher Education Press, Beijing" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" pagination="252 - 269" refId="B19" refString="Wen, J, Ickert-Bond, SM, Nie, Z-L, Li, R, 2010. Timing and modes of evolution of eastern Asian - North American biogeographic disjunctions in seed plants. In: Long, M, Gu, H, Zhou, Z, Eds., Darwin's Heritage Today: Proceedings of the Darwin 200 Beijing International Conference. Higher Education Press, Beijing: 252 - 269" title="Timing and modes of evolution of eastern Asian - North American biogeographic disjunctions in seed plants." volumeTitle="Darwin's Heritage Today: Proceedings of the Darwin 200 Beijing International Conference." year="2010">Wen et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
